    <subfield code="o">45</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">Perturbations of the expansion rate depend on the choice of observers, and the degree of backreaction depends on this [38]. The experimentally measured Hubble rate is not simply related to the expansion rate 3H = θ = nµ</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
    <subfield code="o">45</subfield>
    <subfield code="m">µ, where nµ denotes the normal to the equal time hypersurface. Experiments rather measure distance redshift relations, e.g. dL(z), and infer a Hubble rate from them via the background relation dL(z) = z/H0 + O(z2 ) for small redshifts [39]. Here we neglect this interesting subtlety and simply study whether changes in the expansion rate θ can become large due to clustering. At small redshifts, z 1, this distinction is irrelevant</subfield>
